My Dev Journal: Project Reflections & Breakthroughs

This is where I document the actual reality of building these projects. Looking back, the basics came together pretty smoothly—variables, simple calculations, and core syntax just made sense early on without much friction.

The real shift happened when I hit the intermediate topics. That's where the code started getting a lot more abstract. I found myself slowing down to map out how data was moving, fighting with variable scopes, and spending a lot of time debugging to get my automated tests to pass. But, as I practiced more through more intermidiate python practice, and lately, core projects, and soon advanced applications, i would gradually adapt to it, and it would become less common.

🔍 IB Omniscience Portal
🔹 IB Formula Vault & Search Engine (formula_bank.py)
Why I Built It: A digital database to store and look up academic formulas sorted by topic. It functions as a lightweight database engine that automatically formats user text to block duplicate entries, catches empty inputs before they cause crashes, saves updates to the hard drive in real time, and runs a case-insensitive search that instantly pulls formulas out of layered dictionary structures.
The Experience: This project represented the peak of my procedural programming journey, and it was a massive mental workout. I initially got stuck trying to use a brute-force for loop to scan for duplicate formulas, which accidentally broke the whole function. I had to learn that dictionaries have an internal map, meaning I could completely ditch the slow loop and check for duplicates instantly using a direct in lookup. I also ran into a variable naming collision in my search menu loops that caused a runtime crash, forcing me to learn how to keep my loop variable names perfectly isolated.
What I Actually Learned: This lab taught me how to handle nested dictionaries smoothly (like vault[topic][formula_name] = equation). It also taught me how to use isinstance() to check data types in real time so the interface knows whether to print a simple error string or unpack a full dictionary of results. Most importantly, I learned how to use AI effectively—not to write the code for me, but to act as a peer programmer to help me decode generic error messages and spot hidden syntax traps.

🔹 IB Diploma Grade Tracker & Core Matrix Simulator (ib_grade_tracker.py)
Why I Built It: Tracks a student's full IB academic profile by turning raw assignment scores into weighted class averages and final 1–7 scale grades. It simultaneously checks Extended Essay (EE) and Theory of Knowledge (TOK) marks against a point matrix to calculate bonus points, automatically verifying real-time graduation conditions.
The Experience: This was my first time handling highly complex, real-world rule sheets in code. Building the grade boundaries and the TOK/EE matrix required heavy conditional logic. The tough part wasn't just doing the basic math, but keeping the code organized so that data from one subject didn't accidentally overwrite or corrupt data in another.
What I Actually Learned: I mastered the "separation of concerns" design principle by keeping my file storage, core grade rules, and console menu completely independent of each other. I also learned how to use file streams to read and write permanent JSON data safely without accidentally wiping out the student's existing profile history.

🔹 Assignment Planner (assignment_planner.py)
Why I Built It: A practical tool to manage school assignments and tests by letting me create, delete, view, and modify tasks in a clean list on my screen.
The Experience: This was a fun project because it was something I could actually use in my daily school life. It took the abstract concepts I practiced in earlier labs and turned them into a functional application.
What I Actually Learned: This was my very first introduction to data persistence. I learned how to use Python's json library to save data directly to a physical file on my computer, meaning my assignments stayed saved even after closing the terminal.

