🔍 Basic Python Practice
🔹 Bill Splitter (bill_splitter.py)
Why I Built It: A straightforward calculator utility to figure out exactly what everyone owes at dinner, including tax and tips.
The Experience: The logic was entirely intuitive. I built this out quickly and added simple conditions to prevent errors, like a crash if someone accidentally typed "0" people.
What I Actually Learned: Handled basic user inputs, data type casting (like converting string inputs into floats), and using f-strings to keep outputs clean.

🔹 Movie Ticket Booking Simulator (movie_ticket_booking.py)
Why I Built It: A script that handles seat assignments and ticket prices based on customer age, timing, and available slots.
The Experience: Setting up the conditional logic rules came together smoothly. I mapped out age thresholds and timing slots easily without getting twisted up in the code branches.
What I Actually Learned: Used logical operators (and, or, not) to combine checks cleanly, keeping the execution flow streamlined and easy to follow.

🔹 Caesar Cypher Encoder/Decoder (caesar_cypher.py)
Why I Built It: A text manipulation game that encrypts or decrypts messages by shifting characters along the alphabet.
The Experience: Converting the puzzle rules into actual code was a straightforward process. The main trick was handling the alphabet boundary so characters wrapped from 'Z' back to 'A', which I solved with basic arithmetic.
What I Actually Learned: Got a solid look at character-to-integer conversions using ord() and chr(), along with using the modulo operator (%) to handle looping boundaries.

🔹 Bounty Hunter Mechanics Simulator (bounty_hunter.py)
Why I Built It: A text-based logic loop designed to track player states, inventories, and mission targets.
The Experience: I handled the game state flags and conditional updates without any real issues. The logic flow for updating player inventory maps felt natural to implement.
What I Actually Learned: Worked with flag-based logic systems, tracking variable updates over time, and changing game states based on consecutive user choices.

🔹 Employee Profile Generator (employee_profile_generator.py)
Why I Built It: An automation tool that takes loose, raw employee details and formats them into standardized company profiles.
The Experience: Straightforward string manipulation. Putting variables inside formatting blocks allowed me to standardize input data cleanly without getting stuck on the syntax.
What I Actually Learned: Used core string methods like .strip(), .title(), and .upper() to clean up raw inputs properly.

🔹 Report Card Printer (report_card_printer.py)
Why I Built It: A tool that gathers multiple student grades, calculates the average performance, and prints a formatted card to the terminal.
The Experience: A great exercise in visual layout formatting. The concepts made sense right away, and I used padding parameters to align strings cleanly so the terminal output looks like a structured spreadsheet.
What I Actually Learned: Learned how to use f-string padding tricks (like {:.<20}) to force the console to print perfectly aligned rows and columns every single time.

🔹 User Configuration Manager (user_configuration_manager.py)
Why I Built It: A script that manages application settings securely, making sure preferences are cleaned up and formatted properly while catching runtime errors before they cause a crash.
The Experience: This was my introduction to the CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) model. It reinforced concepts like string formatting and collection management, and I was happy to find that I managed the overall data flow quite smoothly.
What I Actually Learned: I mastered the basic pillars of CRUD, which is a core requirement for real-world software. I also noticed that writing code without getting tripped up by basic syntax errors has become much more natural.

🔹 Medical Data Validator (medical_data_validator.py)
Why I Built It: A strict gatekeeper for a dataset of medical records, checking each entry to ensure no data is corrupted, missing, or improperly formatted.
The Real Challenge: This is where the intermediate difficulty spike really hit me. I struggled with a hidden variable scope issue that took over 40 minutes to track down. I created a constraints dictionary inside the validation function, but accidentally tried to pull keys from it in a completely separate function. The code just kept crashing. I had to slow down, map out where my variables lived and died, and explicitly rebuild the target key set locally where the validation loop runs.
What I Actually Learned: This project forced me to understand variable scope (how variables exist only inside specific functions). It also gave me hands-on practice with more advanced tools like dictionary unpacking (kwargs) and regular expressions (re.fullmatch) to enforce strict text patterns.

🔹 Automated Delivery Drone (automated_delivery_drone.py)
Why I Built It: A simulation tool designed to track a delivery drone's real-time flight coordinates and payload states.
The Real Challenge: Moving past simple variables and understanding data integrity—making sure that critical details like flight coordinates couldn't be accidentally changed mid-flight by other parts of the script.
What I Actually Learned: I finally understood the practical difference between lists and tuples. By locking coordinates into immutable (unchangeable) tuples, I learned how to protect critical data from accidental bugs.

🔹 PIN Extractor (pin_extractor.py)
Why I Built It: A utility designed to dig through messy, unformatted text strings, isolate specific numeric PIN sequences, and verify them.
The Real Challenge: Handling unpredictable user strings. If a user inputs something unexpected, standard string slicing can easily trigger an "out-of-bounds" error and crash the whole program.
What I Actually Learned: I learned how to write robust text-parsing logic and design clean function return structures so the code handles bad data gracefully instead of breaking.

🔹 Number Pattern Generator (num_pattern.py)
Why I Built It: An algorithmic exercise focused on printing specific numeric grids using mathematical logic.
The Real Challenge: Managing nested loops. One minor indentation mistake or counting error can easily create an infinite runaway loop or completely scramble the text alignment in the terminal.
What I Actually Learned: I developed a much stronger mental model of loop execution flow, learning how to step through nested iterations sequentially and control spacing precisely.
